          "title": "The chapter's pastoral theme — postponement as judgment",
          "body": "If Acts 24 has a single applicational center, it is Felix's words: 'Go away for the present, and when I find time I will summon you' (24:25). The most dangerous response to the gospel is not violent rejection but polite deferral. Paul preached *faith in Christ Jesus* (24:24) — the same gospel that saved Cornelius, Lydia, and the Philippian jailer. Felix heard it under direct apostolic exposition with his Jewish wife beside him. He felt its weight. He postponed. And Luke records, with a sharpness that should sober every reader, that the convenient time never came. Hebrews 3:7-8 will state the principle: 'Today, if you hear His voice, do not harden your hearts.' Acts 24 is the case study."
